Model recap

Question you may want to ask if you are a researcher: isFemale a predictor of heart_attack? In public health language, is being Female a risk factor for heart attack (myocardial infarction)?

In last class, we built a simple logistic regression model using glm().

# creates the logistic regression model
model <- glm(formula = heart_attack ~ isFemale, data = heart_study, family = "binomial")
# summarizes/quantifies the model
summary(model)

Model interpretation

Pay close attention to isFemale. In particular, please note the numbers under Estimate (1.3246) and Pr(>|z|) (0.00202).

Questions you could answer:

  1. IsisFemale a statistically significant predictor or contributor to heart attack? Yes, since P-value (0.00202) is less than 0.05.

  2. DoesisFemale increase or decrease odds of heart attack? First we need to exponentiate the estimate from the model: \(e^{1.3246}\) = 3.760681. Since this value exceeds 1, isFemale increases odds of heart attack. In public health language, being female is a risk factor for heart attack.

    # Exponentiate the estimate from the model
exp(1.3246)
    [1] 3.760681

  3. What is the specific increase in odds (interpretation)? The odds of having a heart attack are approximately 3.76 times greater for females than for non-females.

Interpretation for another model

The final model we built in class assesses the impact of both isFemale and age as predictors of heart attack. This logistic regression model quantifies the simultaneous influence of both variables to the outcome of interest (heart attack).

final_model <- glm(formula = heart_attack ~ isFemale + age, 
                   data = heart_study,

  3. What is the specific increase or decrease in odds (interpretation)?

    • After controlling for sex, we estimate that for every 1-year increase in age, the odds of having a heart attack increase by approximately 4.95%.

    • After controlling for age, we estimate the odds of having a heart attack are approximately 5.30 times greater for females than for non-females.

Note: In the above example, there are only two variables. However, if you are modelling using three or more variables, you may keep the language simple (e.g., âAfter controlling for all other variablesâ).

Formal statistical test: Which model is better?

In model 1 above (model), we modeled:

heart_attack ~ isFemale

In model 2 above (final_model), we modeled:

heart_attack ~ isFemale + age

When you have a model that simply adds another variable on top of another model, those two models are called nested. When models are nested, you can formally assess the model performance via a test called likelihood ratio test. Below show you how to run the test

# feed anova() with the two models to compare then add at the end: test = "LRT"
anova(model, final_model, test = "LRT")
Analysis of Deviance Table

Model 1: heart_attack ~ isFemale
Model 2: heart_attack ~ isFemale + age
  Resid. Df Resid. Dev Df Deviance  Pr(>Chi)    
1        98     125.31                          
2        97     103.62  1   21.688 3.207e-06 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

How to read the results above?

  1. Compare the deviance: Model 1 (isFemale) has a residual deviance of 125, while Model 2 (isFemale + age) has a residual deviance of 103. Since Model 2 has a lower residual deviance, model 2 is the better model (i.e., lower residual deviance means better fit for the underlying data). The follow-up question now becomes: is Model 2 a statistically significant better model than model 1?
  2. Look at the p-value: Since the p-value for the Likelihood Ratio Test is less than 0.05, model 2 is a statistically significant better model than model 1.

Again: Likelihood ratio test is only appropriate for nested models (i.e., models that essentially builds on top of one another). In our example above, we compared isFemale vs isFemale + age).

An example of non-nested models you canât compare via this likelihood ratio test:

Non nested model 1:

heart_attack ~ isFemale

Non nested model 2:

heart_attack ~ age

Using logistic regression as a classifier

So far, we have used logistic regression as a statistical model to quantify the impact of independent variables (e.g., isFemale, age) on binary outcomes (heart attack vs no heart attack). The language of interpretation involves odds.

Some machine learning analysts or engineers use logistic regression as a classifier tool (e.g., cancer vs not cancer, spam email vs non spam email).

How logistic regression is typically used in classifier tasks:

  1. Use some data (often called training data) to create a logistic regression model.
  2. Use additional data (often called test data) to assess ability of logistic regression model to predict outcomes.

    • Calculating probabilities of outcome for each data row.

    • Pick a probability cut off (e.g., typically 0.50 or 50%). If 50% is picked, this is equivalent to saying: if the predicted probability for outcome exceeds 50%, you are predicted to have had a heart attack.

    • Adjust probability cut off if desired.

In this example, let us assume that final_model is the best model we could build to predict heart_attack. We are essentially done with part 1 of the two steps I presented above.

Now, let use another data set as our test data to quantify the ability of our model to predict heart_attack.

Before we go any further, let us go over two common terminology in statistics and machine learning with respect to classifiers:

  • Sensitivity (true positive rate) is the probability of a positive test/prediction, conditioned on the individual truly being positive. This is a measure of a test/algorithmâs ability to identify true positives: # of predicted cases out of true positive cases

  • Specificity (true negative rate) is the probability of a negative test/prediction, conditioned on the individual truly being negative. This is a measure of a test/algorithmâs ability to identify true negatives: # of predicted negatives out of true negative cases

Addendum post class: sensitivity vs specificity

Earlier, we created this table from the R data frame we generated:

Predicted - Heart Attack Predicted - No Heart Attack
Actual - Heart Attack 24 (True Positive) 16 (False Negatives)
Actual - No Heart Attack 16 (False Positive) 44 (True Negatives)

Another way to calculate sensitivity:

True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives)

Another way to calculate specificity:

True Negatives / (True Negatives + False Positives)

Adjusting probability cut off

Why would you adjust probability cut off? It depends on your goal. If your goal is to increase your machine learningâs ability to identify true positives or real cases (sensitivity), you may want to lower the initial probability cut off (e.g., 0.4) to increase the modelâs sensitivity. But it is important to know that there is specificity vs sensitive trade-off. Let us see what happens if we lower the probability cut off for predicting heart attack to 0.4:

test_heart_data_v3 <- test_heart_data |>
  mutate(probability_outcome = predict(final_model, # model you want to predict
                                       newdata = test_heart_data, # test data
                                       type="response")) |>
  mutate(predicted_outcome = ifelse(probability_outcome > 0.4, 1, 0))

test_heart_data_v3 |>
  group_by(heart_attack, predicted_outcome) |>
  summarise(counts = n())

`.groups` argument.

New specificity: 0.57 or 57% (because 34/60) | Old specificity: 73%

Splitting one data frame into training vs test data

We first loaded a csv file into the R environment as heart_study, which we eventually used to create the final_model. Then we loaded another csv file into the R environment as test_heart_data to assess our modelâs ability to predict probabilities of heart attack.

What is more often done in the real world is:

  1. You are provided one giant file which you load into R.
  2. Once the file is loaded into R, you split the resulting data frame into two data frames with a 50-50 allocation.

The code below shows you an example on how to split one csv file into to two data frames with a 50-50 allocation.

ggstatsplot: Statistical Tools To Compare Multiple Groups

I originally wasnât planning to cover this. But we are going over âcookie-cutterâ way of doing statistics to make statistics accessible to students, so now, I want you to be aware of the ggstatsplot package, one of my favorite packages in R.

Before proceeding, let us remind ourselves of the penguins data from the palmerpenguins package.

The ggstatsplot package is really useful to assess whether or not the difference in average values of numeric variables across two or more groups are statistically significant.

If you are interested in assessing whether body_mass_g significantly differ across the three penguin species, you may run the following script below:

# run in R console if not installed: install.packages("ggstatsplot")
library(ggstatsplot)
You can cite this package as:
     Patil, I. (2021). Visualizations with statistical details: The 'ggstatsplot' approach.
     Journal of Open Source Software, 6(61), 3167, doi:10.21105/joss.03167
ggbetweenstats(
  data  = penguins,
  x     = species, # the categorical variable you want to compare across
  y     = body_mass_g, # numeric variable you want to compare
  title = "Distribution of body mass across penguin species"
)

How do you read this plot? The plot (combination of box plot and violin plot) tells you it used a statistical test called Games-Howell to do pairwise comparison tests across the groups you identified. âBar shown: significantâ tells you that pairwise differences via pairwise comparison with bars above were found to be statistically significant and there are two bars with p-values (this tells you that difference in two pairwise comparisons are statistically significant).

Formal statistical interpretation: The difference in body mass between Adelie and Gentoo (average of 3700 grams vs 5076 grams) is statistically significant. Likewise, the difference in body mass between Chinstrap and Gentoo (average of 3733 grams vs 5076 grams) is statistically significant.

ggstatsplot: two groups only

Hereâs another code that uses penguins. This time, it only compares two groups via sex (Female vs Male penguins).

ggbetweenstats(
  data  = penguins,
  x     = sex, # the categorical variable you want to compare across
  y     = body_mass_g, # numeric variable you want to compare
  title = "Distribution of body mass between male and female penguins"
)

Important note: Since there are two groups only, you should not expect a bar above to assess pairwise differences. Instead, look at the p-value provided below the graph title. Since p-value provided is 4.79e-16, which is lower than 0.05, the difference in body mass between male and female penguins is statistically significant.

Additional note: nonparametric statistics

Typical statistical tests we employ have what are called parametric assumptions (e.g., variable distribution of our sample comes from a population that is bell curved or normally distributed). Again, this is not a statistics class. But if you want to be on the safer side, you can specify ggbetweenstats() to use what are called non-parametric statistical tests to compare the groups. If the data you use has a lot of outliers or very skewed, including type = "nonparametric" inside ggbetweenstats() might be a good idea. Non-parametric tests typically compare the median instead of the mean to assess whether the difference in median across groups are statistically significant.

ggbetweenstats(
  data  = penguins,
  x     = sex, # the categorical variable you want to compare across
  y     = body_mass_g, # numeric variable you want to compare
  type = "nonparametric",
  title = "Distribution of body mass between male and female penguins"
)
